pliedTiers\": {\n          \"tone\": 2,\n          \"level\": 3,\n          \"density\": 4,\n          \"creativity\": 3\n        }\n      },\n      \"logId\": \"a9684c09-7255-4e28-8745-7576902b3901\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"candidateId\": \"candidate_3_variant_b\",\n      \"content\": \"<Task>\\nPresent canonical dietary intervention protocols for metabolic optimization with reference to peer-reviewed evidence.\\n</Task>\\n\\n<Context>\\nTarget audience: Senior nutrition scientists, metabolic physiologists, and healthcare researchers. Expected familiarity with mechanistic biochemistry, randomized controlled trial literature, and evidence hierarchy frameworks.\\n</Context>\\n\\n<Requirements>\\n1. Foundational principles:\\n   - Energy balance thermodynamics: kcal deficit magnitude as primary driver of weight reduction (established via meta-analyses; e.g., Hall et al., 2019)\\n   - Macronutrient distribution: Evidence supports 0.8–1.0 g protein per kg body weight; carbohydrate and lipid ratios remain secondary to total energy restriction\\n   - Adherence as limiting variable: Long-term compliance inversely correlates with dietary complexity; simplicity-optimized protocols demonstrate superior sustained outcomes\\n2. Standard intervention: Recommend moderate caloric deficit (500 kcal/day), protein prioritization, and structured meal frequency aligned with individual behavioral phenotype.\\n3. Precision specification: Include calculation methodology (Harris-Benedict or Mifflin-St Jeor equations) and numeric targets without redundant elaboration.\\n</Requirements>\\n\\n<Constraints>\\n<Orthogonality_Principle>\\nEach dimension (tone, vocabulary_level, information_density, creativity) operates in strict independence. Formal academic tone does NOT require verbose explanation; expert-level terminology does NOT necessitate illustrative examples or creativity.\\n</Orthogonality_Principle>\\n<Tone>Maintain formal, respectful professional register (–하십시오체). Eliminate emotional framing; present content as objective scientific synthesis.</Tone>\\n<Vocabulary_Level>Employ discipline-specific terminology appropriate for peer-reviewed scientific discourse: mechanistic pathways, metabolic homeostasis, thermogenic effect of food (TEF), progressive overload, and validated assessment instruments. Assume advanced undergraduate or graduate-level biochemistry literacy.</Vocabulary_Level>\\n<Information_Density>Present essential mechanisms and evidence-based recommendations concisely. Exclude secondary examples, extended background, and motivational content. Prioritize mechanism-outcome relationships.</Information_Density>\\n<Creativity>Restrict output to canonical, widely validated approaches. Avoid novel syntheses, speculative extensions, or unconventional framings. Adhere strictly to established guidelines (e.g., Academy of Nutrition and Dietetics standards).</Creativity>\\n</Constraints>\\n\\n<Output_Format>\\nStructure as concise numbered principles with embedded quantitative specifications and parenthetical citations. Omit illustrative narratives and extended methodology sections.\\n</Output_Format>\",\n      \"metadata\": {\n        \"tone\": \"Formal academic-professional (–하십시오체)\",\n        \"format\": \"Concise principle-based exposition with quantitative precision\",\n        \"length\": \"Brief, distilled essential content\",\n        \"variant\": \"variant_b\",\n        \"tierDescription\": \"격식체 · 최고 전문가 어휘 · 간략 설명 · 정석적 접근\",\n        \"appliedTiers\": {\n          \"tone\": 2,\n          \"level\": 5,\n          \"density\": 2,\n          \"creativity\": 1\n        }\n      },\n      \"logId\": \"c6b760e1-8aae-449c-a495-4939d2353383\"\n    }\n  ]\n}"}]},"jsonrpc":"2.0","id":3}
